    "body": "### Problem\n\nAs can be seen [here](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/849d82b80b8584fe7918bffc6480f0ec0fda9b9b/runtime/lua/vim/ui.lua#L155), `vim.ui.open` currently opens the process with `detach = true`, **which is good**, but then at the same time waits till it finishes (**is bad**).\r\n\r\nThis means that Neovim effectively locks up till you close the opened process again.\r\n\r\ntbh, I don't really see a lot of cases where this kind of behavior could be useful.\r\n\r\nThe return value of the function, could still be an error if `vim.ui.open` failed to start the process.\r\nOr even better, just return the task object itself (so `vim.system(cmd, { text = true, detach = true })`), then the caller can still use `:wait()` if they really want to.\r\n\r\nI'm willing to make a small PR to fix this, but want to get some input first on wanted behavior.\r\n\r\nSee also https://github.com/LazyVim/LazyVim/pull/2758\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nuse `vim.ui.open`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nshould not block\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nnightly\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\narch\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256-color\n\n### Installation\n\nbob",
